<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#2f2f4f">Originally posted by Nuelaan doAevum on 04-04-2001 09:42 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">On a blue server, there are no 'right' answers.

It comes down to "are people gonna be self-centered, short-tempered, arrogant and megalomanical twits?"

Most often, they will and are.

Thus you have the PNP (Play Nice Policy), /petitions, guild flame wars, and all of that unpleasantness.  You have nice people (who play nice and try to consider others, and how others will consider them) who get regularly shafted by the twits.

I play on Tallon Zek.  It's a red server, in case you didn't know.

We have no PNP.  Right now, one of the top guilds has decided they're not going to allow anyone else to achieve a cleric epic.  Why?  Because they have four in their guild and there are less than four others on the entire server.

Every time Nag spawns, and then again when Rage is due, a huge pk war has been errupting in and around SolB, for a few weeks now.  I'd rather settle things like this, than in *any* of the ways bluebies settle things.

Why?

Because we can settle things ourselves, without whining to GMs or the server.  After an issue comes to head on TZ, it's always clear who won and who lost.  I might not like the occasional random PK attack from some empty-headed twit who thinks that kind of thing is funny (team pk), but I'd rather be kicked out of an area because the other people were more powerful than having to whine and petition about "they have our camp, waa waa waa make them share".

Nothing personal to you bluebies, of course.  But I'd much rather be killed and have to scoot than get all frustrated over being helpless to do anything about others' arrogance.

Besides, nothing says I/we (my team) always loses; sometimes we win.  So it works out ok.  If you can defend your 'camp', your 'zone', then you get to stay; this you do by making the others leave.  If you can't defend it, time to find other locales.

Simple, neh?
</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
